The paper deals with the representation and morphing of plane graphs, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of geometric objects to represent vertices and the focus on the existence of a morph between two representations suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of discrete structures (cs.DS) and graph theory (cs.GT). The algorithmic aspect of the paper, specifically the polynomial-time algorithm provided, suggests that it may also be relevant to the study of algorithms and complexity (cs.DM). Finally, the use of piecewise linear morphs and the computation of linear morphs suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of simulation and modeling (cs.SI).
